		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2017"></a><br><code>sle2017/paper23</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Virtual textual model composition for supporting versioning and aspect-orientation</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/RobertBill.html">Robert Bill</a>, <a href="../profile/PatrickNeubauer.html">Patrick Neubauer</a>, <a href="../profile/ManuelWimmer.html">Manuel Wimmer</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136037">10.1145/3136014.3136037</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s core topic is composing textual models virtually to support versioning and aspect-oriented separation.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> It is motivated by maintenance tasks and versioning scenarios where code/model redundancy and irrelevance hinder evolution.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Virtual composition entails mapping/synchronizing between base artifacts and composed virtual views.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5h.html"><span class="tagL">T5H: Usability</span></a><ul><li> It targets improved developer cognition by hiding redundancy/irrelevance in composed views (usability for maintenance).
</li></ul></li></ul>
